 Light &amp; Magic animated film, which sounds like a great idea, and it was, especially with Roger Deakins serving as visual consultant, which is why the lighting is so amazing. But the reason I wanted to talk about this is the unique approach they took in production, which they described as emotion capture. Instead of doing the usual process where an actor is isolated in a booth playing off only the director, actors performed their scenes all together as they would making a live-action film. The behind-the-scenes sort of looks like a quirky theater troupe having a blast, and all the dialogue recorded this way absolutely added a lot of life and the ability to ad-lib and shift ideas on the fly, again, as you would with any live-action production. The animators were thrilled about this, too, since they now had a treasure trove of references from the actual cast. So, instead of the typical method of an animator filming themselves and acting out the motion for reference, they were able to pull that directly from the mannerisms of the actual performer for any given moment. And there's loads of behind-the-scenes showing them do this, capturing the film while playing, and I think it pays off in the final film. As always, the through-line across all of these films isn't some single technological breakthrough. It's a consistent philosophy of illusion rooted in craftsmanship and problem-solving. The actors are physically interacting with the effects, wearing rigs, reacting to puppets, performing in moving sets, and that human performance is exactly what sells it. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; Now, that's what I'm talking about. &gt;&gt; But that's it for today. If you want more amazing effects, we've got a playlist in the notes below with all our other episodes, and we just started a brand new channel called Page One and Beyond. It's a new show that takes a deep dive into the elements that make some of our favorite films stand out. If you dig this show, you're going to love that one, so check the notes for that in the links as well. And until next time, don't forget to write, shoot, edit, repeat. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; I'll see you later. Ta-ta.

