, I went from cutting stand-ups in 30 to 45 minutes to right around 10 minutes. And since I already have my project set up from before, the sound and color are already completed as well. So, in just 10 to 15 minutes, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; we have stand-ups ready with final color and sound. So, now I'll jump back to my main episode timeline and do my scene edit detection to bring back my cuts like before, and I'm ready to move on to the next step. Adding zooms or cut-ins is another needlessly time-consuming task. The high cuts will always do a digital scale up or down to make it feel like a new angle like this right here. Now, we don't do it on every cut because B-roll hides most of them, but it's easier to take away than add. So, I'm going to come in here to auto zoom, handle the same setup, validate. Now, in here I'm going to select on the cut. Then down here, I'll set where I want it to zoom and at what scale. Which does remind me, I see a lot of people using this technique, but they don't scale enough. They'll go from like 100 to 110. And that feels like an odd jump cut, like they didn't finish the move. And I kind of go at a 30% rule. For instance, we have the camera right here. We wanted to shift to a new angle, say over here on my side, you're going to want to move the camera about 30° at least. Otherwise, it just feels like an odd jump cut. And the same goes for a digital zoom like this. So, instead of going from 100 to 110, something like 100 to 130 like this right here feels a lot more correct and fluid. But jumping back into auto cut, want an actual zoom that we see. I just want to cut in. I'll select jump cut right here. Then you can turn on a subtle handheld look if you want. I don't. But then, where you want the adjustment layer with this action to be placed. And I'm going to select above track one, then apply. And the best part about this is that it places the zoom control on an adjustment layer using transform. So, where I don't want it, I just de