Subjective versus objective perspective is something I've been thinking about a lot lately, and it's something I'm always thinking about when planning my coverage for any project. These are two different approaches that will radically change how any given moment is experienced by the audience. It's the difference between seeing the events as an objective spectator or being inside, feeling the subjective force of the moment. So, I want to take a look at the differences, how I've been thinking about them, and at the end, I'm going to give my recipe for getting the right coverage for any scene every time. To make it simple, an objective shot shows you what's happening, clear and neutral. A subjective shot tells you how to feel about it, similar to music. Music can tell the audience how to feel about what they're watching. So much so that it can be overdone with the music's hand getting too heavy, which some called Mickey Mouse, which comes from the early days of Disney when every action Mickey made was supported by music. The difference between objective and subjective can be as simple as frame size and depth of field. For instance, if I have these two characters talking, Josh is in the power position, Justin feeling inferior, an objective way to handle this would be in a twoot, a bit wider with deep depth of field. And if I cut in, I'm keeping both characters in the same sort of framing. But if I wanted to get subjective, I can place the camera a bit lower on Josh, and when I come to Justin, I can be tighter and a bit higher. When the scene gets to the height of Justin feeling inferior, I can move in with shallow depth of field and even higher angle. The low angle makes Josh larger in frame and the high angle makes us look down at Justin. Again, that's a very simple and kind of obvious example, but it can get far more complex, pulling every element in to deepen that emotional immersion. Oenheimer is an incredible example of that and of subjective film making in general. Now, let's pause for a second. This isn't a video essay. I don't do those. And the reason I don't is, and this is on topic, art is massively subjective. Why a filmmaker chose something and even how a viewer responds to that is a very subjective act and not entirely possible to capture in any objective bottle. So what we're talking about here is how I see things as a director myself. And since we are disclaimering a shot isn't entirely subjective or objective either, but more of a range between those two things since it's maybe not possible to have an entirely objective shot. So, we're really talking about how much you turn the volume up on subjectivity or not. But back to Nolan. This film is so subjective that Nolan wrote the entire script in first person using I throughout as if Oppenheimer was the one telling you the story. And this scene in the second half of the film is both my favorite and a perfect example. Nolan really makes us feel this moment. And like I said before, it's not only the framing, it's what's inside it. Like the flickering background, the intensely shallow focus, the overexposed moments. It's also heavily in the sound, which I think sound can force subjectivity even more, but that's an episode for another day. But every element is pushing this into a highly subjective world. Imagine this moment shot more objectively. Still a great scene, but you'd be one of the people in the stands watching it unfold and making your own judgments. Instead, Nolan turned his celebratory speech into an anxietyridden moment of horror by putting us inside the character's mind. We could pull this back to simplicity with, say, a character suddenly getting a jolt of pain in their head. We could shoot it like this, detached, or we could snap in, use shallow focus and a tight frame to bring the viewer into his experience. And of course, it's not just close-ups that will do this, like POV shots. It's one of the many tools that can help you in achieving that result. And