did before with another known film. Though again, it's impossible to be fully objective, but we can compare a highly subjective moment like this one to a more pulledback objective construction like this moment from Manchester by the Sea. We're an observer here outside of his actions, and it's incredibly impactful. So, neither is better than the other. It's about knowing when to use the right tool for the job. Another massively important factor is to know whose subjective perspective we're in. And this is true of your entire story. One of the most important factors of any scene, writing, and directing, and editing, is knowing whose point of view we're telling it from. This could be an untethered observer. It could be one of the characters. It could jump throughout the scene, but you have to know. Another simple example could be two characters talking again, but one is struggling to hold back violence. If I were to shoot this from Josh's perspective, I'd give him a close-up in this scene and not Justin. In that close, we see Josh's eyes shift. And then we cut to his POV as Justin grips the couch trying to hold back his anger. If we shift our perspective to Justin, I'll give him the close-up this time. And when I shoot him gripping the arm of the couch, I'll shift my angle to the side, make it tighter and more shallow, like Justin is feeling it, not seeing it. Then one more shot here, we have sweat rolling down his face. And again, he's feeling that, not seeing it. So, the way that I'm approaching this, at least in my mind, when it's on Josh's perspective, I'm showing what he's seeing. With Justin, I'm showing what he's feeling. And those are two very different scenes. Shifting a little bit here, but still entirely related. Often when you're on set, the shot list has to be rethought, especially when you are lowbudget and running gun. So, a little coverage recipe that I stick to in those moments to make sure that I have what I need is triangle coverage plus specials. Triangle coverage is exactly what it sounds like. To keep it simple, for a conversation scene between two people, it would be a shot of each and a master. And the specials would be these extra shots like we've been showing throughout the episode. It's that extra seasoning that you don't necessarily need to finish an edit, like the close on the hand or the sweat, but they are going to elevate it and carry the intention that helps you tell the story the way that you want. So on set, when time is running out and I have to toss the plan and move fast, this frame of thinking has always gotten me to an end result that I was happy with. Whether that's action or dialogue, I know if I have it from those three points, I have it. Which those points are setups, which means I could get a wide medium close from each point or two people are sitting next to each other and then I could get singles on each of them and it's still from that point. Now, this isn't a best case scenario situation. This is not how I shot list. when I have my way, it's very specific coverage just to that scene. But when time is not on my side, this is a great safety net to have in my back pocket and is one that has saved me many times, more than once. You can see it in my short films, Proximity, UFO, Ya, Ballistic, and a bunch of others. Probably every one of them if I'm being honest. In each instance, we were running out of time. So, I threw out the shot list and shifted to my triangle coverage, and we made our day. But again, with that triangle coverage, those specials that give subjectivity to the scene are the thing that really make it come alive for me and become the connected tissue to the audience. Whether that's as obvious as Oppenheimer or the Dutch angle in Mission Impossible telling us things are wrong or as subtle as crushing your depth of field. And of course, sound is a massive factor here. Oppenheimer and Saving Private Ryan both use sound in incredibly subjective and immersive ways that take t